description:
I'm on Windows 11, latest VScode version, I don't write flutter or dart, therefore I don't have any flutter or Dart extensions.

### Steps to reproduce
Open an empty file, don't save it on disk. paste any HTML snippet containing Javascript like this one

```
<script>
  let countdownInterval;

  // Start or restart the countdown with `seconds` total time
  function startCountdown(seconds) {
    // Clear any existing interval
    if (countdownInterval) {
      clearInterval(countdownInterval);
    }

    // Show the countdown container
    const countdownEl = document.getElementById('countdown');
    countdownEl.style.display = 'block';

    // Reset and trigger the bar animation
    const bar = countdownEl.querySelector('.countdown-bar');
    bar.classList.remove('animate');
    bar.style.setProperty('--duration', `${seconds}s`);
    void bar.offsetWidth;  // Force reflow to restart the animation
    bar.classList.add('animate');

    // Update the text label
    const label = document.getElementById('countdown-label');
    let timeLeft = seconds;
    label.textContent = formatTime(timeLeft);

    // Decrement every second
    countdownInterval = setInterval(() => {
      timeLeft -= 1;
      label.textContent = formatTime(timeLeft);

      if (timeLeft <= 0) {
        clearInterval(countdownInterval);
        label.textContent = 'Completed!';
      }
    }, 1000);
  }

  // Simple helper to format seconds (customize as you wish)
  function formatTime(sec) {
    return sec + 's remaining';
    // Or if you prefer mm:ss:
    // const m = Math.floor(sec / 60);
    // const s = sec % 60;
    // return `${m}:${s.toString().padStart(2, '0')} remaining`;
  }

  // Example: if you're using htmx for SSE
  // (in your SSE definition, set `event: "#progress"`)
  document.body.addEventListener('htmx:sseMessage', function (evt) {
    // The SSE message data is available in evt.detail.data
    // We'll regex to find <time>...</time>
    if (evt.detail && evt.detail.data) {
      const match = evt.detail.data.match(/<time>(\d+)<\/time>/);
      if (match) {
        // If the time is given in minutes, multiply by 60
        // If the time is already in seconds, pass it directly
        const minutes = parseInt(match[1], 10);
        const seconds = minutes * 60;  
        startCountdown(seconds);
      }
    }
  });
</script>

```


On my Vscode as soon as you paste this snippet, it's detected as Dart, sometimes I get linting errors too.

I don't know if this bug can be fixed or not, you know more, language detection is hard, especially when you mix HTML and CSS and JS I would guess. 

If this can be fixed, great, if not then I would suggest allowing the user to turn off auto language detection for a particular language. For example I don't do Flutter or Dart, I have a feeling that if I can just turn off Dart language detection, the system would recognize the file correctly as javascript, it's just that Dart has a higher probability now.

Besides, I only write a few languages, if I can either disable the languages I don't use and are supported by VSCode or enable only the language I do use (Blacklist/Whitelist). This could improve the performance of the editor, maybe? I don't know

Another solution, is if the editor is not 100% of the file type, then let the file open in plain text, at least then the user won't see any linting errors and such. Plain text is fine and that's because if you're opening a temporary file to check some code, you don't need any highlighting or linting but if the file is not detected correctly, then often all you see are errors. Especially if you're using inline error extension like [error lens](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=usernamehw.errorlens) and most people are using such extensions these days.

I had a bug raised against Dart where the debugger shows threads as "paused on entry" when they should not be. The DAP traffic looks good:

```
// Start
[5:17:21 PM] [DAP] [Info] <== {"seq":21,"type":"event","body":{"reason":"started","threadId":3},"event":"thread"}
// Pause
[5:17:21 PM] [DAP] [Info] <== {"seq":43,"type":"event","body":{"allThreadsStopped":false,"reason":"entry","threadId":3},"event":"stopped"}
// Resume
[5:17:21 PM] [DAP] [Info] <== {"seq":78,"type":"event","body":{"allThreadsContinued":false,"threadId":3},"event":"continued"}
```

Yet the UI shows the thread as paused. I was able to reproduce this in MockDebug. It seems to only occur when the events occur close together (if I add delays, it doesn't seem to happen):

```ts
// Start additional threads, pause on entry, continue.
for (var i = 2; i < 5; i++) {
	this._threads.push(new Thread(i, `Thread ${i}`));
	this.sendEvent(new ThreadEvent('started', i));
	this.sendEvent(new OutputEvent(`Thread ${i} started\n`));
	this.sendEvent(new StoppedEvent('entry', i));
	this.sendEvent(new OutputEvent(`Thread ${i} stopped on entry\n`));
	// await this.delay(1); // Uncomment this to fix it
	this.sendEvent(new ContinuedEvent(i, false));
	this.sendEvent(new OutputEvent(`Thread ${i} continued\n`));
}
```

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0fb97a17-fbeb-4507-b414-34ed1f3311c1)

Full repro is here:

https://github.com/DanTup/vscode-mock-debug/tree/repro-dart-code-5397 / https://github.com/DanTup/vscode-mock-debug/commit/04f4764e853cbee2b09ca28c110c423fb4b99fd0

This felt a bit like https://github.com/microsoft/debug-adapter-protocol/issues/513 to me, but that actually turned out to be caused by `allThreadsStopped` defaulting to `true`. I don't believe that's the case here because in the real project where this happens (Dart debugger), we set both `allThreadsStopped` and `allThreadsContinued` to `false` (though I haven't set `allThreadsContinued` in the MockDebug example because it doesn't seem to be available in the constructor... I don't believe that's the issue though as `allThreadsContinued` seems to default to false and the delay shouldn't fix the issue in that case).

